    oneLiner: "A distributed system can guarantee at most two of three: Consistency, Availability, and Partition tolerance.",
    body: "Consistency: every read gets the most recent write. Availability: every request gets a response (not necessarily the latest data). Partition tolerance: the system works despite network failures between nodes. In a network partition (which WILL happen), you must choose: refuse some requests to stay consistent (CP) or serve potentially stale data to stay available (AP). You can't have both during a partition. Traditional databases choose CP. Systems like Cassandra and DynamoDB choose AP.",
